{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":340092,"duration_api_ms":368804,"ttft_ms":84385,"num_turns":6,"result":"My grounding confirms the key facts: Pudgalavada's \"inexpressible person\" as a genuine intra-Buddhist position, the Svatantrika-Prasangika dispute over whether Madhyamaka even asserts theses, and that comparative religion acknowledges intra-traditional diversity but does not formalize it as a measurement gate. Here is my single structured idea record.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"title\": \"First Ask If a Path Agrees With Itself\",\n  \"idea_type\": \"contradiction\",\n  \"source_basis\": [\n    \"Run mode: Critique. The active frontier (translation strain as a test of convergence) is heavily elaborated, so this run hunts for a structural failure in the scoring rather than adding another strain variable.\",\n    \"Thinking-method source: Zhuangzi's perspectival humility and Daoist non-forcing, used as a lens to refuse fixing a whole tradition to one representative point. Critique of the lens: non-forcing can dissolve every stable position into mere perspective, which would over-fragment traditions that do settle operative positions; corrected with SN 22.95 style disciplined examination, which still asks what is actually trained at a given stage.\",\n    \"Contrasting reasoning discipline: effect-size logic from statistics, where a between-group difference counts as real only if it exceeds within-group variance. This supplies the missing denominator for strain scores.\",\n    \"Primary-text comparison (intra-Buddhist spread): SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta refuses to treat any aggregate, including consciousness, as self, while the Pudgalavada (Vatsiputriya, Sammitiya) posited a pudgala or person that is neither the same as nor different from the aggregates and is inexpressible. https://suttacentral.net/sn22.59/en/sujato ; https://iep.utm.edu/pudgalavada-buddhist-philosophy/\",\n    \"Primary-text comparison (intra-Advaita spread): Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23 names an unseen knower, read by Shankara as self-luminous direct recognition, while a scriptural-testimony (shabda pramana) emphasis treats the witness as established through revealed instruction rather than spontaneous self-disclosure. The comparison reveals that the intra-Advaita gap on how the witness is known, and the intra-Buddhist gap on whether any subject is authorized, can rival the cross-tradition atman/anatta gap the strain protocol claims to measure.\",\n    \"Internal-posture evidence: the Svatantrika-Prasangika dispute over whether Madhyamaka asserts a thesis at all (Bhavaviveka vs Candrakirti, surveyed in Dreyfus and McClintock, The Svatantrika-Prasangika Distinction: What Difference Does a Difference Make?), showing that even a tradition's assertion posture is internally contested.\",\n    \"Codex prior art treated as orthogonal: Translation Strain as a Load Test for Convergence (d92d2f0f6455ac53); A Shared Word Is Not Two Witnesses (provenance gate); No Word Travels Alone (receiver wound). All measure deformation between traditions or its causes; none measures instability within a tradition as a control.\",\n    \"Comparative-method prior art: Jonathan Z. Smith, In Comparison a Magic Dwells; Freiberger's rectification step; and comparative religion's general acknowledgment of intra-traditional diversity, which notes the diversity but does not make measured within-tradition variance the threshold any between-tradition score must clear.\",\n    \"Modern human-condition grounding: docs/modern-human-condition.md on digital comparison and meaning loss; the surgeon-general social-connection advisory on isolation.\"\n  ],\n  \"original_claim\": \"Translation-strain comparison has a numerator and no denominator. Before you can say that two traditions converge or clash on a claim unit, you must measure how much that same unit varies inside each tradition, across its sub-schools, stages of practice, and polemical eras. If the internal spread is as wide as the gap you found between the two traditions, then your convergence-or-divergence verdict is mostly an artifact of which internal version you happened to pick, not a cross-tradition signal. So Lumenary should now hold that a strain score is only admissible once between-tradition strain has been shown to exceed within-tradition variance for the same unit; otherwise the comparison should be labeled selection-dependent and given no evidential weight.\",\n  \"why_it_might_be_new\": \"Existing strain work measures the deformation between two traditions, and the provenance gate asks whether an apparent similarity came from historical contact. This adds a different and orthogonal control: whether the unit is even stable enough within one tradition to be compared. A comparison can pass the provenance gate (genuinely independent) and still fail this variance gate (the chosen claim unit is internally contested enough that another legitimate reading would flip the verdict). The move imports effect-size reasoning into spiritual comparison: comparative religion already notes intra-traditional diversity, but does not require a measured within-tradition spread as the denominator that every between-tradition strain score must clear.\",\n  \"critique\": \"The statistical analogy is loose: claim units are not random samples from a distribution, so within-tradition variance is metaphorical, and there is no clean way to compute it. Worse, weighting every textual variant equally inflates the denominator. Pudgalavada was eventually marginalized, and a minority or scholastic position may not deserve the same weight as the operative mainstream that practitioners actually train. Some traditions do settle a dominant working position at a given stage despite live scholarly disputes, so treating internal variance as always large would itself distort by flattering fragmentation. The denominator therefore must be weighted by how operative a variant is, not by its mere existence in the record, and that weighting is contestable enough that a motivated comparer could tune it to reach either verdict. The control is real but it relocates the judgment rather than removing it.\",\n  \"epistemic_labels\": [\n    \"textual\",\n    \"interpretive\",\n    \"analogical\",\n    \"empirical-adjacent\",\n    \"speculative\"\n  ],\n  \"scores\": {\n    \"novelty\": 0.6,\n    \"generativity\": 0.85,\n    \"cross_tradition_support\": 0.72,\n    \"logical_coherence\": 0.86,\n    \"explanatory_compression\": 0.8,\n    \"empirical_adjacency\": 0.5,\n    \"practice_testability\": 0.74,\n    \"counterargument_quality\": 0.88,\n    \"source_reliability\": 0.66,\n    \"publishability\": 0.72\n  },\n  \"next_research_directions\": [\n    \"If this model is right, then when independent coders are each given a different but legitimate internal variant of each tradition (Theravada anatta versus Pudgalavada person; Shankara self-luminosity versus scriptural-testimony Advaita), they should return contradictory convergence verdicts for high-variance units and agreeing verdicts for low-variance units such as the bare instruction to attend to the breath. If convergence verdicts stay stable regardless of which internal variant is selected, the model is weakened.\",\n    \"Operationalize within-tradition variance with operative weighting: code each internal variant by how central it is to lived practice at a stated stage, not by its presence in the textual record, then test whether weighted variance still rivals the cross-tradition gap in the atman/anatta case.\",\n    \"Run the variance gate and the provenance gate together on the same pairs to confirm they are orthogonal: find at least one pair that passes provenance (independent) but fails variance (internally unstable), and one that passes variance but fails provenance.\",\n    \"Test whether assertion posture (does a tradition hold theses) behaves as a continuous contested parameter rather than a fixed property, using the Svatantrika-Prasangika case as the calibration example.\"\n  ],\n  \"teaching_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"Ask if a path agrees with itself\",\n    \"teaching_line\": \"Before you decide two paths agree or clash, ask whether each path even agrees with itself.\",\n    \"doctrine_claim\": \"A claim that two traditions converge or contradict is unreliable until you know how widely each tradition disputes that same point inside its own house.\",\n    \"body\": \"Someone tells you two faiths say the same thing, or that they flatly disagree. Before you believe it, look closer. Pick up either tradition and you will often find it arguing with itself: different teachers, schools, and centuries answering the question in different ways. If a path disputes a point among its own people, one quote cannot speak for the whole. Do not let a single sentence stand in for a living argument. When you compare, compare the range, not the slogan; and notice that a tidy agreement or a clean contradiction is sometimes only the two quotes you happened to meet first.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Meaning loss and cynical dismissal, or its mirror, rootless all-is-one universalism, triggered when a person reads short comparative claims online and concludes either that the traditions secretly agree or that they are hopelessly contradictory.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"Reflective cross-tradition readers and seekers, especially people whose footing is unsettled by influencer or AI summaries that flatten many traditions into one verdict.\",\n    \"pressure_survived\": \"Survives the atman versus anatta case, where the intra-Buddhist range (strict not-self versus the Pudgalavada inexpressible person) and the intra-Advaita range (self-luminous recognition versus knowing the witness through scripture) rival the cross-tradition gap; survives prior comparative-method acknowledgment of internal diversity by turning that diversity into a measured gate rather than a caution.\",\n    \"falsifying_pressure\": \"Weakens if convergence verdicts stay stable no matter which legitimate internal variant of each tradition is chosen, or if practitioners' operative positions turn out far narrower than the textual disputes suggest, so that the internal spread is mostly scholastic and not lived.\",\n    \"status\": \"under_dialogue\",\n    \"tags\": [\n      \"comparison\",\n      \"internal-disagreement\",\n      \"digital-comparison\",\n      \"meaning-loss\",\n      \"critique-mode\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"practice_candidate\": {\n    \"title\": \"The self-agreement check\",\n    \"practice_line\": \"Before trusting a comparison, find where each tradition argues with itself about it.\",\n    \"purpose\": \"To keep a single quote from standing in for a whole tradition, and to steady a person against both rootless all-is-one feelings and cynical it-is-all-contradictory dismissal.\",\n    \"target_human_problem\": \"Meaning loss, digital comparison, and the urge to abandon practice after meeting contradictory or falsely harmonized quotes.\",\n    \"target_cohort\": \"Reflective readers and seekers who compare traditions through books, feeds, or AI summaries.\",\n    \"non_fit\": \"Not for acute distress or crisis. Not a substitute for actually practicing one path. Not for people whose real problem is endless analysis and avoidance of commitment; they need to choose and practice, not compare more. Not a way to settle scholarly disputes the person has no sources to judge.\",\n    \"duration\": \"10 minutes\",\n    \"frequency\": \"Only when you encounter a strong claim that two traditions agree or contradict, no more than twice a week.\",\n    \"minimum_attempt\": \"Try it on three separate comparisons before judging whether it helps.\",\n    \"steps\": [\n      \"Write the comparison you heard in one line: X and Y both say, or X and Y contradict on, this exact point.\",\n      \"For each tradition, find one place where its own teachers, schools, or earlier and later texts disagree on that same point.\",\n      \"Write the internal range for each tradition in one short line.\",\n      \"Ask: is the gap between the two traditions clearly wider than the gap inside each of them?\",\n      \"If it is not clearly wider, hold the comparison loosely; it may be a choice of quotes rather than a finding.\",\n      \"Choose one path's actual practice to try in your own life this week instead of waiting for the comparison to be settled.\"\n    ],\n    \"notice\": [\n      \"Whether the urge to announce they agree or it is all confused loosens.\",\n      \"Whether you feel freer to commit to one practice without first resolving the comparison.\",\n      \"Whether you start hearing single quotes as one voice in an argument rather than the whole tradition.\"\n    ],\n    \"caution\": \"Do not let this become a reason never to commit; endless comparison is its own trap. Stop if it feeds rumination, paralysis, or a feeling that nothing can be trusted.\",\n    \"weakens_if\": \"It increases analysis paralysis, or it adds nothing beyond the ordinary humility a careful reader already has.\",\n    \"risk_level\": \"low\",\n    \"status\": \"seed\",\n    \"tags\": [\n      \"comparison\",\n      \"internal-disagreement\",\n      \"low-risk\",\n      \"meaning-loss\",\n      \"digital-comparison\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"tests\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Within-tradition variance prior-art search\",\n      \"test_type\": \"prior-art\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"Comparative theology and comparative religion should acknowledge intra-traditional diversity and warn against projecting similarity, but should not already require measured within-tradition variance of the same claim unit as the explicit threshold any between-tradition convergence score must exceed. If that exact control already exists with predictive use, novelty should fall below 0.35.\",\n      \"result\": \"Preliminary search found strong general acknowledgment of intra-traditional diversity (Stanford pluralism entry, anthropology of religion sources) and the Svatantrika-Prasangika and Pudgalavada disputes, but no source making within-tradition variance the formal denominator for strain scoring. The effect-size framing appears new to this domain; full audit incomplete.\",\n      \"impact\": \"revises\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Close-read Jonathan Z. Smith, Freiberger, Dreyfus and McClintock, and recent comparative-method work for any formalized variance-as-denominator control before raising novelty.\",\n      \"status\": \"complete\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Variant-swap convergence coding\",\n      \"test_type\": \"falsification-attempt\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"Give independent coders the same cross-tradition pair but assign each a different legitimate internal variant of each tradition. For high-variance units (the self in Buddhism, the witness in Advaita, grace versus effort in Christianity) coders should produce contradictory converge-or-diverge verdicts; for low-variance units they should agree. If verdicts are stable across variant assignment, the variance gate adds nothing and the model is weakened.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Build a small codebook listing two or three legitimate internal variants per tradition per unit, then run blind coding with variant assignment randomized.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Legal-transplant analogue\",\n      \"test_type\": \"cross-domain\",\n      \"target_type\": \"idea\",\n      \"prediction\": \"Legal concepts that are internally contested within a single system (good faith, due process, reasonableness) should yield less stable cross-system convergence verdicts and more failed transplants than concepts with a settled internal meaning, even when the shared term looks identical. If cross-system convergence is predicted just as well by shared terms regardless of internal contestation, the analogy and the variance gate lose force.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Score a handful of legal concepts by within-system dispute level, then compare against documented harmonization disputes and failed transplants.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Self-agreement check practice report\",\n      \"test_type\": \"practice-report\",\n      \"target_type\": \"practice\",\n      \"prediction\": \"For reflective seekers unsettled by comparative claims, three uses of the self-agreement check should reduce both all-is-one certainty and cynical dismissal, and should make commitment to one practice feel more available. If it increases analysis paralysis or rumination, the practice is weakened or must be narrowed.\",\n      \"result\": \"pending\",\n      \"impact\": \"pending\",\n      \"next_action\": \"Collect short before-and-after reports from readers who recently encountered a strong comparative claim, screening out acute distress and chronic avoidance.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"ed803f6b-242b-4ce3-95a2-58c9dab88eef","total_cost_usd":4.166744749999999,"usage":{"input_tokens":3774,"cache_creation_input_tokens":524153,"cache_read_input_tokens":33717,"output_tokens":23555,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":524153,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":9144,"cache_read_input_tokens":16905,"cache_creation_input_tokens":269461,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":269461},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":217910,"outputTokens":1655,"cacheReadInputTokens":0,"cacheCreationInputTokens":0,"webSearchRequests":4,"costUSD":0.266185,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputToken